1
00:00:52,458 --> 00:00:55,750
[舒缓的背景音乐]

2
00:01:22,583 --> 00:01:25,083
[Swisher] 在硅谷有很多关于起源的故事

3
00:01:25,083 --> 00:01:29,417
这些故事里的公司，有着很正确的理念，但却完完全全

4
00:01:29,417 --> 00:01:34,750
诞生在了错误的时间，然而他们还是推动了所有事情的发展

5
00:01:34,750 --> 00:01:38,125
[Markoff] 有很多故事定义了硅谷

6
00:01:38,125 --> 00:01:43,208
世上有很多传奇，而 General Magic 就是其中一个

7
00:01:45,375 --> 00:01:48,125
[Sculley] 你必须相信、必须要自豪

8
00:01:48,125 --> 00:01:52,458
必须绝对地说服自己

9
00:01:52,458 --> 00:01:54,917
你将改变世界运行的轨迹

10
00:01:54,917 --> 00:01:58,125
如果你一直待在安全区，也从未失败

11
00:01:58,125 --> 00:02:02,333
那有很大可能就是碌碌无为度过一生

12
00:02:05,583 --> 00:02:09,750
[Joanna] 无论我们的梦想多夸张，事实是你能
No matter how big we dreamed, the fact that you could touch

13
00:02:09,750 --> 00:02:12,125
触碰到数以亿计的 the lives of billions, billions,

14
00:02:12,125 --> 00:02:13,959
it was vaguely imaginable,

15
00:02:13,959 --> 00:02:18,000
but the scale of it was inconceivable.

16
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:21,458
[Hershenson] 你为什么要关心 General Magic 的故事？

17
00:02:21,458 --> 00:02:25,000
因为这个故事关系到现实世界里很基本的东西
is because it involves something fundamental,

18
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:29,667
那就是……失败兵不是一切的结束

19
00:02:29,667 --> 00:02:31,875
失败其实是一个开始

20
00:02:34,959 --> 00:02:39,000
[Hoffman] 这个故事至今萦绕在经历者们的心中

21
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:45,000
就是因为他们知道他们当时做的事情是正确的

22
00:02:47,250 --> 00:02:51,917
[Hershenson] 它失败了？或者说，这个公司失败了，但这些想法没有

23
00:02:51,917 --> 00:02:56,375
为这些想法工作的人们没有失败，那……这件事算失败吗？

24
00:03:00,375 --> 00:03:05,375
[戏剧性的配乐]

25
00:03:46,542 --> 00:03:48,417
[铃声响起]

26
00:04:21,625 --> 00:04:23,000
[Tony] 我当时正在念高中

27
00:04:24,375 --> 00:04:27,125
应该是 16 岁吧当时

28
00:04:27,125 --> 00:04:31,041
我完全不想上学，在家的日子只要一起床

29
00:04:31,041 --> 00:04:35,000
就在电脑前，学习编程和一切跟电脑有关的东西

30
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:39,375
还跟我朋友讲这些，我是个极客，你知道吗，就是《菜鸟大反攻》里那种

31
00:04:39,375 --> 00:04:45,458
从三四岁开始，每个周末我不是在造东西就是在拆东西

32
00:04:45,458 --> 00:04:49,125
Soapbox derby racer, or we could repair
lawnmowers or what have you.

33
00:04:49,125 --> 00:04:55,166
But with this I could create new things. I could sit there
and I could program a game,

34
00:04:55,166 --> 00:05:00,250
or I could program graphics, I could do things and you spoke
a language no one else knew

35
00:05:00,250 --> 00:05:02,875
and you could tell people about it and they were like, wow.

36
00:05:04,542 --> 00:05:07,834
然后就是 Mac，
And then it was the Mac and it was all about the Mac.

37
00:05:09,166 --> 00:05:10,917
[whispering] What is that?

38
00:05:14,625 --> 00:05:19,208
There were names of people like Andy Hertzfeld, Joanna Hoffman,
Bill Atkinson,

39
00:05:19,208 --> 00:05:24,375
rock stars in Rolling Stone, but had nothing to do with
music. They were my heroes.

40
00:05:24,375 --> 00:05:28,500
我的名字叫 Andy Hertzfeld, 我在 1978 年买了 Apple II 并且爱上了它

41
00:05:28,500 --> 00:05:35,250
And went to work for Apple in 1979 and was lucky enough to help design the Macintosh.

42
00:05:35,250 --> 00:05:37,375
You have to go
and find out more about them,

43
00:05:37,375 --> 00:05:40,208
and how can I go work with them,
because I wanted to be
like them.

44
00:05:41,583 --> 00:05:45,625
[Chariots of Fire
by Vangelis playing]

45
00:05:45,625 --> 00:05:48,208
[audience cheering]

46
00:05:48,208 --> 00:05:53,834
[computerized voice] Hello,
I am Macintosh. It sure is
great to get out of that bag.

47
00:05:53,834 --> 00:05:55,125
[crowd cheering]

48
00:05:55,125 --> 00:05:57,625
1984 年 1 月 24 日

49
00:05:57,625 --> 00:06:00,166
Macintosh 正式公开发布
uh, the Macintosh was being publicly introduced

50
00:06:00,166 --> 00:06:03,709
第一次在世人面前揭开面纱
to the world, for the very first time.

51
00:06:03,709 --> 00:06:06,375
[Joanna] You know what I remember? We were sitting here

52
00:06:06,375 --> 00:06:13,542
and there was this roar,
just sort of like a sound
wave coming, coming at us.

53
00:06:13,542 --> 00:06:19,417
It was a culmination of years of
work, of years of expectation.

54
00:06:19,417 --> 00:06:20,583
This was it.

55
00:06:20,583 --> 00:06:24,125
What we are trying to do
with Macintosh is take away

56
00:06:24,125 --> 00:06:27,208
yet another barrier
to usage of personal computers.

57
00:06:27,208 --> 00:06:29,625
One of the neatest things
about Macintosh was
we had a chance

58
00:06:29,625 --> 00:06:32,500
to change the way that people
thought of computers.

59
00:06:32,500 --> 00:06:35,291
We called it the computer
for the rest of us,

60
00:06:35,291 --> 00:06:38,333
because computers
weren't for ordinary people.

61
00:06:38,333 --> 00:06:42,458
We thought we had a chance to
make a difference. Steve Jobs
just drummed it into us.

62
00:06:42,458 --> 00:06:45,041
He was just such
a brilliant motivator.

63
00:06:45,041 --> 00:06:48,083
The greatest people are
self-managing. They don't
need to be managed.

64
00:06:48,083 --> 00:06:50,542
What they need is a common vision.

65
00:06:50,542 --> 00:06:53,750
Once they know what to do, they'll go figure out how to do it.

66
00:06:53,750 --> 00:06:57,041
[Andy] We truly believed with every fiber of our being

67
00:06:57,041 --> 00:07:02,458
that if we can solve that problem of, um, making computers accessible

68
00:07:02,458 --> 00:07:05,875
to an ordinary person by making them easy enough to use,

69
00:07:05,875 --> 00:07:08,291
we could truly change the world.

70
00:07:10,291 --> 00:07:11,583
[Joanna] But behind the scenes,

71
00:07:11,583 --> 00:07:14,792
behind that facade, things were changing.

72
00:07:14,792 --> 00:07:17,792
Steve Jobs 深陷政治斗争中
Steve Jobs was involved in palace politics.

73
00:07:17,792 --> 00:07:20,792
That was much bigger at that moment than the Mac.

74
00:07:20,792 --> 00:07:24,959
I was just too tunnel-visioned
to be able to appreciate that.

75
00:07:24,959 --> 00:07:27,959
[Andy] I got a phone call, like
around 10:00 a.m. in the morning

76
00:07:27,959 --> 00:07:33,458
from someone on the Mac team
saying, "You won't believe this,
but Steve got fired."

77
00:07:38,125 --> 00:07:45,000
The core team was stunned.
That said, things were a mess
in many ways.

78
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:48,709
But Steve and John Sculley
didn't agree about
what to do with it.

79
00:07:48,709 --> 00:07:52,333
Fights escalated to the point
where the board told Sculley

80
00:07:52,333 --> 00:07:54,709
that he had to remove Steve.

81
00:07:57,625 --> 00:08:01,458
Um, wrenching decision
for everyone,

82
00:08:01,458 --> 00:08:05,250
both Steve and Sculley
and everyone close to them.

83
00:08:05,250 --> 00:08:06,792
[Joanna] Since the Mac,

84
00:08:06,792 --> 00:08:09,834
really I think we were all
looking for the next thing

85
00:08:09,834 --> 00:08:13,375
-because it really
jaded us for anything else.
-[Andy] Yes.

86
00:08:13,375 --> 00:08:16,667
[Joanna] Any other project
that kept coming up,
kinda fizzled very quickly

87
00:08:16,667 --> 00:08:19,625
because it didn't have
the grandness of the vision,

88
00:08:19,625 --> 00:08:23,834
it didn't have the grandness
of potential impact.

89
00:08:23,834 --> 00:08:25,291
And now what?

90
00:08:30,875 --> 00:08:33,792
[soft music]

91
00:08:42,458 --> 00:08:45,792
Good evening, I'm Marc Porat.

92
00:08:45,792 --> 00:08:48,750
Today many people believe
that information tools

93
00:08:48,750 --> 00:08:53,041
are the third technology
to change the course
of civilization.

94
00:08:53,041 --> 00:08:57,291
Changing our relationship
to nature, to each other,

95
00:08:57,291 --> 00:09:00,000
to the very way
we experience reality.

96
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:03,750
The Aspen Institute attracted
some of the most amazing people.

97
00:09:03,750 --> 00:09:07,917
It had a place where they could
speak freely to each other
in private.

98
00:09:07,917 --> 00:09:11,750
Cyrus Vance or Henry Kissinger
or the Shahbanou of Iran or--

99
00:09:11,750 --> 00:09:16,000
Very, very powerful people that
you would never expect to meet.

100
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:19,333
Those were the people, that was,
that was the teaching there,
you could,

101
00:09:19,333 --> 00:09:23,917
and in fact,
you were responsible and had
a mandate to invent the future.

102
00:09:23,917 --> 00:09:28,959
Because the future your parents
handed you, that was broken.

103
00:09:28,959 --> 00:09:35,750
And so that started me in the
track of saying, "What can I do
to create the future?"

104
00:09:38,250 --> 00:09:42,625
There comes a moment
where for some reason
you are in the future,

105
00:09:42,625 --> 00:09:47,000
and you see something very, very clearly. You just see it.

106
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:49,959
That's what happened to me,
and I went into the future,

107
00:09:49,959 --> 00:09:54,125
and I saw the world which,
which I thought was very real
and very tangible.

108
00:09:54,125 --> 00:10:00,083
And I stood
in that moment, inside it,
and I looked around my-- me,

109
00:10:00,083 --> 00:10:04,792
and it was there, it was
all there. It was basically
the General Magic vision.

110
00:10:09,166 --> 00:10:14,375
It was gonna be so revolutionary
that it would take over
the world.

111
00:10:14,375 --> 00:10:20,750
So this book I wrote in 1989
and this was a compilation
of, of the ideas.

112
00:10:20,750 --> 00:10:23,333
And it was called
Pocket Crystal.

113
00:10:24,792 --> 00:10:28,834
And this is
what we came up with in 1989.

114
00:10:30,834 --> 00:10:34,834
And there it is,
we really had it. [chuckles]

115
00:10:37,875 --> 00:10:38,834
We definitely had it.

116
00:10:43,875 --> 00:10:46,500
[clink-clank noises]

117
00:10:52,417 --> 00:10:55,375
Business is just stories. That's what people do, they tell stories.

118
00:10:55,375 --> 00:10:59,500
And they-- and the ones who tell the most compelling stories are the ones who,

119
00:10:59,500 --> 00:11:04,834
you know, end up making the most progress forward and Marc was a great story teller.

120
00:11:04,834 --> 00:11:09,041
After Steve Jobs left in 1985,
a lot of people were pretty
depressed,

121
00:11:09,041 --> 00:11:12,125
and they wondered what Apple's
future was going to be like.

122
00:11:12,125 --> 00:11:15,458
You know, could Apple still
go on without Steve Jobs there?

123
00:11:15,458 --> 00:11:19,875
Marc was one of the first people
to see that computing in
the future was gonna be,

124
00:11:19,875 --> 00:11:23,041
not just about computation,
it was gonna be about
communications,

125
00:11:23,041 --> 00:11:25,875
it was gonna be about content
and it was gonna be very,
very personal.

126
00:11:25,875 --> 00:11:28,333
Something that you could
hold in your hand.

127
00:11:28,333 --> 00:11:32,667
[Marc] And it was a telephone,
it was essentially going
to be a smartphone

128
00:11:32,667 --> 00:11:35,625
with a lot
of intelligence in it.

129
00:11:35,625 --> 00:11:38,333
Imagine a personal computer,
with applications organized

130
00:11:38,333 --> 00:11:40,417
around these personal
wants and needs.

131
00:11:40,417 --> 00:11:43,792
An object through which you
communicated with yourself
about everything

132
00:11:43,792 --> 00:11:48,709
that you're thinking about.
It was the way you reached out
and touched other people,

133
00:11:48,709 --> 00:11:54,166
and it was the way that
you reach beyond that
into the larger world.

134
00:11:54,166 --> 00:11:59,792
Marc always came with his giant
red book, uh, and he would thumb
through the pages

135
00:11:59,792 --> 00:12:03,959
and, uh,
he was able to romance me,

136
00:12:03,959 --> 00:12:07,792
he was able to romance
Bill Atkinson, Andy Hertzfeld.

137
00:12:07,792 --> 00:12:09,542
[answering machine] Please leave
a message and we will return

138
00:12:09,542 --> 00:12:11,875
your call
as quickly as possible.

139
00:12:11,875 --> 00:12:15,333
I saw a message on my answering
machine from Bill Atkinson

140
00:12:15,333 --> 00:12:17,500
who was my mentor
at Apple, my hero.

141
00:12:17,500 --> 00:12:19,792
"I just saw
the greatest thing ever.

142
00:12:19,792 --> 00:12:22,417
You got to come back to
Apple to work with me on it."

143
00:12:22,417 --> 00:12:27,417
And the very next day Marc Porat
came over to my house with his
models and stuff.

144
00:12:27,417 --> 00:12:30,458
Wouldn't it be nice,
if all these notes,
which are very useful,

145
00:12:30,458 --> 00:12:33,250
I could have with me
when I needed them.
Wouldn't it be nice I suppose,

146
00:12:33,250 --> 00:12:38,291
if letters that were important,
arrived, fell out of the sky.

147
00:12:38,291 --> 00:12:43,041
[Andy] I was a little skeptical
at first, because Marc
is such a slick salesperson,

148
00:12:43,041 --> 00:12:45,542
but I saw that, hey,
this is pretty cool.

149
00:12:45,542 --> 00:12:48,875
[Joanna] And when I saw this,
the concept and
I talked to Marc,

150
00:12:48,875 --> 00:12:50,959
I got the same butterflies
in my stomach.

151
00:12:50,959 --> 00:12:55,291
The same feeling that I had
when I first encountered
the Macintosh.

152
00:12:55,291 --> 00:12:59,375
This book was not just ideas,

153
00:12:59,375 --> 00:13:02,834
not just possibilities,

154
00:13:02,834 --> 00:13:05,542
but this was a complete
and thorough collection

155
00:13:05,542 --> 00:13:09,333
of the vision of the future,
scenario by scenario.

156
00:13:09,333 --> 00:13:14,250
Marc said, "We are gonna
create what comes after
the personal computer."

157
00:13:14,250 --> 00:13:17,875
"John," he said, "I think this
can be the future of Apple,

158
00:13:17,875 --> 00:13:20,125
but I'm not sure it
can be done inside of Apple.

159
00:13:20,125 --> 00:13:22,208
I think it's got to be
a separate company."

160
00:13:22,208 --> 00:13:26,000
I helped Marc get the investment
from the Apple board.

161
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:28,709
So Apple ended up
spinning out General Magic.

162
00:13:28,709 --> 00:13:33,333
This was the beginning
of what became, I think,
the most important company

163
00:13:33,333 --> 00:13:36,166
to come out of Silicon Valley
that nobody had ever heard of.

164
00:13:36,166 --> 00:13:39,875
[upbeat music]

165
00:13:45,834 --> 00:13:47,667
[Markoff] There was this
aura of secrecy.

166
00:13:47,667 --> 00:13:49,583
We knew the people that went in.

167
00:13:49,583 --> 00:13:51,208
We knew they were smart people.

168
00:13:51,208 --> 00:13:55,083
You know it had Apple's
fairy dust sprinkled on it.

169
00:13:55,083 --> 00:13:56,709
So we had no idea what it was,

170
00:13:56,709 --> 00:14:00,083
but by the rumors
it seemed just captivating.

171
00:14:00,083 --> 00:14:03,333
There's this company,
it has Andy and Bill and,

172
00:14:03,333 --> 00:14:05,542
and they're going off
to do something.

173
00:14:05,542 --> 00:14:09,959
And I was like, "I don't know
what they are doing yet,
but I know I need to be there."

174
00:14:09,959 --> 00:14:14,041
I was dressed up,
I had my suit coat and a tie,

175
00:14:14,041 --> 00:14:16,208
and I was there at about
8:30 in the morning.

176
00:14:16,208 --> 00:14:19,250
I knocked on the door,
no one answered,
so I opened the door

177
00:14:19,250 --> 00:14:22,208
and it was very quiet and I'm
like, "Where is everybody?"

178
00:14:22,208 --> 00:14:26,417
And I look over and there are
two people in this office

179
00:14:26,417 --> 00:14:31,083
and they had been there all
night, and they looked at me
with these dazed eyes

180
00:14:31,083 --> 00:14:36,792
and they were like, "We're
not hiring." And that was it.

181
00:14:36,792 --> 00:14:41,250
[Stern] Everybody in
the valley knew that Magic was--
was doing something really cool,

182
00:14:41,250 --> 00:14:44,125
and really hot, they didn't
know exactly what it was.

183
00:14:47,875 --> 00:14:52,083
Everybody wanted to be there
and people literally would
sleep on the doorstep

184
00:14:52,083 --> 00:14:54,291
to try to get an interview
or get into the building.

185
00:14:54,291 --> 00:14:57,041
[interviewer] I mean from your
perspective, is this unique?

186
00:14:57,041 --> 00:14:59,125
Or is this everywhere in
the valley and not so special?

187
00:14:59,125 --> 00:15:02,250
No, no it's
not everywhere in the valley!

188
00:15:02,250 --> 00:15:06,000
The best, the brightest
the coolest, the smartest.

189
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:09,000
[Bill] Hi Megan, welcome aboard.
[laughter]

190
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:11,000
Oh, smile!
You are on "Candid Camera."

191
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:13,458
[Megan] I was always
building things.

192
00:15:13,458 --> 00:15:18,542
I come from a long line
of engineers. And so the idea
of going to Silicon Valley

193
00:15:18,542 --> 00:15:22,166
and learning
with these extraordinary
people how to make products

194
00:15:22,166 --> 00:15:24,709
and create things
and do just amazing things,

195
00:15:24,709 --> 00:15:27,041
that's what I wanted to do,
it was drawing me.

196
00:15:30,500 --> 00:15:36,458
Andy Hertzfeld had gotten
my name as a Mac developer,
and so he called me.

197
00:15:36,458 --> 00:15:39,500
[Andy] I'm sorry to offend you
with this Non Disclosure
Agreement...

198
00:15:39,500 --> 00:15:41,917
But he couldn't tell me what it
was, and I was just thinking,

199
00:15:41,917 --> 00:15:44,041
"Oh my god I am talking to
Andy Hertzfeld right now."

200
00:15:46,959 --> 00:15:50,291
My parents are looking at
me going, "I don't know anything

201
00:15:50,291 --> 00:15:53,750
about this General Magic.
Why don't you go to
a company you know, like

202
00:15:53,750 --> 00:15:58,417
IBM or Microsoft, can't you go
there, where it's well known?"

203
00:15:58,417 --> 00:16:01,333
I'm like, "No, I wanna go
work for General Magic."

204
00:16:01,333 --> 00:16:05,250
He would call me ten, fifteen
times a day just begging,

205
00:16:05,250 --> 00:16:08,625
"Please get my resume"
and he would just ask me,

206
00:16:08,625 --> 00:16:11,250
"Please, I will not stop
until I work there."

207
00:16:11,250 --> 00:16:13,667
[Tony] And so I go into
the interview, first thing in,

208
00:16:13,667 --> 00:16:18,875
people sat me down on the floor,
ripped my tie off, ripped off
my jacket and said,

209
00:16:18,875 --> 00:16:23,333
"That's not how we work here."
So I go home back to Michigan,
packed up all my things,

210
00:16:23,333 --> 00:16:26,000
and put them in a car
and then I'm like,
I got to hear something.

